Population-specific effects of randomness on isoform expression

J. Ignacio Lucas LledÃ³

23/12/2019

One of the conclusions in 2019-04-03 was that there is a significant interaction between the effects of the regime and of the original population. That means that not all populations responded equally to a specific selective regime. We need to take this into account to decide what contrasts are interesting. Not only the isoforms that are on average differently expressed in regular than in random environments are interesting. The specific response of each random population may have biological meaning.

On 2019-04-03 we also determined that there are no isoforms with a significant interaction between selective regime and hatching condition. This may be a simple consequence of the fact that not all populations respond similarly to the selective regimes: in this situation, there are just not enough replicates to detect an interaction between regime and hatching condition.

Isoforms expressed on average differently between random and regular regimes

When I first tested the effect of randomness on expression level using model 4 and 6 on 2019-04-03, I tested for a significant second coefficient, which corresponds to the expression level of a sample from original population 1 under a random regime, relative to the expression level of population 3, under a regular regime. That does not seem to be what I want. To make it easier to express a contrast that compares all random populations to all regular ones, I will use a different model.

counts <- read.table(COUNTS_FILE, row.names=1, header=TRUE)
regimePop <- factor(c('random1',  'random1',  'random2',  'random2',
                      'regular1', 'regular1', 'random3',  'random3',
                      'regular2', 'regular2', 'regular3', 'regular3'))
diapause   <- factor(rep(c("hatch","diapause"), 6))
diapause   <- relevel(diapause, "hatch")

# Filtering
y <- DGEList(counts=counts, group=regimePop)
y <- calcNormFactors(y, method="TMM")
threshold <- 5.0 / (min(y$samples$lib.size) / 1000000)
keep <- rowSums(cpm(y) > threshold) >= 4
y <- y[keep, ,keep.lib.sizes=FALSE]
NumOfTags <- dim(y)[1]
design7 <- model.matrix(~ 0 + regimePop + diapause)
row.names(design7) <- names(counts)
reactable(design7, columns=list(
  regimePoprandom1 = colDef(name='Random.1'),
  regimePoprandom2 = colDef(name='Random.2'),
  regimePoprandom3 = colDef(name='Random.3'),
  regimePopregular1 = colDef(name='Regular.1'),
  regimePopregular2 = colDef(name='Regular.2'),
  regimePopregular3 = colDef(name='Regular.3'),
  diapausediapause = colDef(name='diapause')))
y7 <- estimateDisp(y, design7)
fit7 <- glmQLFit(y7, design7)
randomness <- glmQLFTest(fit7, contrast = c(1/3, 1/3, 1/3, -1/3, -1/3, -1/3, 0))

By treating populations independently, model 7 neither assumes nor estimates whatever common effect populations in the same regime may share.

Instead of reporting the number of significantly regulated isoforms under a specific FDR, I report here the overall, FDR-independent, estimated fraction of regulated isoforms. There are ways to estimate the number of true null hypotheses even when there is a dependence structure among tests. I found the package cp4p (Gianetto et al.Â 2016. Proteomics, 16(1), 29-32.), that does exactly that. The SLIM method Want et al.Â 2011, is supposed to be adequate for datasets with dependence structure, but I think here it overestimates the proportion of non-regulated isoforms.

randomness.pi0 <- estim.pi0(randomness$table$PValue)
randomness.pi0

   ggtitle('Random versus regular. Model 7.')

rm(z1)

According to this test, at least 38 and up to 70% of isoforms are differentially expressed on average between regular and random regimes.

Isoforms always expressed differently in a random population than in the average regular population

The scatterplot of p-values is not expected to produce any visible correlation, unless for the smallest p-values. Plotting p-values in logarithmic scale does show that man isoforms differentially expressed in any population under the random regime is also differentially expressed in the other populations in the same regime.

pairs(data.frame(rand1=log(random1$table$PValue),
                 rand2=log(random2$table$PValue),
                 rand3=log(random3$table$PValue)),
      pch=".", main='Log(p-values)')

What about the log-fold change? Does the random regime change isoform expression in the same direction in all populations? Yes:

pairs(data.frame(rand1=random1$table$logFC,
                 rand2=random2$table$logFC,
                 rand3=random3$table$logFC),
      pch = ".", main = 'Log(fold change)')

Given the large number of regulated isoforms, I can use a conservative FDR to compare the most significantly regulated isoforms among populations in the random regime.

significant <- cbind(randomness = topTags(randomness, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none', adjust.method='fdr')$table$FDR <= 0.1, 
                     random1 = topTags(random1, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none', adjust.method='fdr')$table$FDR <= 0.1,
                     random2 = topTags(random2, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none', adjust.method='fdr')$table$FDR <= 0.1,
                     random3 = topTags(random3, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none', adjust.method='fdr')$table$FDR <= 0.1)
vennDiagram(vennCounts(significant), main='FDR=0.1')

Writing up the results

A large proportion of isoforms up- or downregulated in any population under the random regime is also regulated in at least one other population under the random regime. The first and third populations in the random regime are more similar among them. Population 2 being the one with more isoforms regulated by the selective regime is also the one with the largest proportion of exclusively regulated isoforms.

I should save the results of the glmQLFTest() to run the functional analysis on the lists of regulated isoforms in a different session. I think itâs also good practice to save a plain text copy of the main tables, to allow inspection outside R.

save(randomness, random1, random2, random3, file = 'isoforms/RegimeEffect_model7.RData')
write.table(topTags(randomness, n=NumOfTags)[[1]],
            file = 'isoforms/randomness.txt',
            quote = FALSE)
write.table(topTags(random1, n=NumOfTags)[[1]],
            file = 'isoforms/random1.txt',
            quote = FALSE)
write.table(topTags(random2, n=NumOfTags)[[1]],
            file = 'isoforms/random2.txt',
            quote = FALSE)
write.table(topTags(random3, n=NumOfTags)[[1]],
            file = 'isoforms/random3.txt',
            quote = FALSE)
